  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Cebes, from Thebes, Friend of Socrates (Pl. Crit. 45b, Xen. Mem. 1,2,48
    3,11,17)together with his companion Simmias Socrates' main interlocutor in Plato's ‘Phaedon’.....The dialogue entitled 
    Pínax and falsely attributed to C. was probably written during the 1st cent. At the first author to attest to it is Lucian (De Mercede Conductis 42
    Rhetorum Praeceptor 6). In the dialogue, an anonymous speaker reports how in a sanctuary of Cronus a likewise anonymous old man explained
    to him a painting on display there, representing in allegorical form the false and the correct path in life...." Döring, Klaus (Bamberg). 
    "Cebes." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and
    Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2011. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 03 October 2011</mads:note>
